lph E. Davison\n\n'''2 fleet carriers'''\n: ''[[USS Franklin (CV-13)|Franklin]]'' (Capt. J.M. Shoemaker)\n:: ''Air Group 13'' (Cmdr. R.L. Kibbe)\n:: VF-13: 34 [[F6F Hellcat]] fighters, 4 [[Grumman F6F Hellcat#Further development|F6F-xN Hellcat]] night fighters\n:: VB-13: 31 [[SB2C Helldiver]] dive bombers\n:: VT-13: 18 [[TBM Avenger]] torpedo bombers\n: ''[[USS Enterprise (CV-6)|Enterprise]]'' (Capt. Cato D. Glover)\n:: ''Air Group 20'' (Cmdr. D.F. Smith)\n:: VF-20: 35 [[F6F Hellcat]] fighters, 4 [[Grumman F6F Hellcat#Further development|F6F-xN Hellcat]] night fighters\n:: VB-20: 34 [[SB2C Helldiver]] dive bombers\n:: VT-20: 19 [[TBF Avenger]], 5 [[TBM Avenger]] torpedo bombers\n\n'''2 light carriers'''\n: ''[[USS San Jacinto (CVL-30)|San Jacinto]]'' (Capt. M.H. Kernodle)\n:: ''Air Group 51'' (Cmdr. C.L. Moore)\n:: VF-51: 19 [[F6F Hellcat]] fighters\n:: VT-51: &nbsp;&nbsp;7 [[TBM Avenger]] torpedo bombers\n: ''[[USS Belleau Wood (CVL-24)|Belleau Wood]]'' (Capts. John Perry)\n:: ''Air Group 21'' (Lt. Cmdr. V.F. Casey)\n:: VF-21: 25 [[F6F Hellcat]] fighters\n:: VT-21: &nbsp;&nbsp;9 [[TBM Avenger]] torpedo bombers\n\n: 1 heavy cruiser: ''[[USS New Orleans (CA-32)|New Orleans]]'' (Capt. J.E. Hurff)\n: 1 light cruiser: ''[[USS Biloxi|Biloxi]]'' (Capt. P.R. Heineman)\n\n'''Screen''' (Capt. V.D. Long)\n: 11 destroyers\n:: 3 [[Gleaves class destroyer|Gleaves-class]]: [[USS Wilkes (DD-441)|''Wilkes'']], [[USS Nicholson (DD-442)|''Nicholson'']], [[USS Swanson|''Swanson'']]\n:: 3 [[Gridley class destroyer|Gridley-class]]: [[USS Gridley (DD-380)|''Gridley'']], [[USS McCall (DD-400)|''McCall'']], [[USS Maury (DD-401)|''Maury'']]\n:: 5 [[Bagley class destroyer|Bagley-class]]: [[USS Bagley (DD-386)|''Bagley'']], [[USS Helm (DD-388)|''Helm'']], [[USS Mugford (DD-389)|''Mugford'']], [[USS Patterson (DD-392)|''Patterson'']], [[USS Ralph Talbot (DD-390)|''Ralph Talbot'']]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n*{{cite book\n | last      = Morison\n | first     = Samuel Eliot\n | year      = 1958 \n | title     = Leyte, June 1944 - January 1945\n | volume    = XII\n | series    = History of United States Naval Operations in World War II\n | publisher = Little, Brown and Co.\n | location  = Boston\n | isbn      = 0-7858-1313-6}}\n*{{cite book\n | last      = Stille\n | first     = Mark\n | year      = 2016\n | title     = US Navy Light Cruisers, 1941-45\n | publisher = Osprey Publishing, Ltd. \n | location  = Oxford\n | isbn      = 978-1-4728-1140-0}}\n\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1944]]\n[[Category:Pacific Ocean theatre of World War II]]\n[[Category:Naval aviation operations and battles]]\n[[Category:Battle of Leyte Gulf]]\n[[Category:Naval battles of World War II involving Japan]]\n[[Category:Naval battles of World War II involving the United States]]\n[[Category:October 1944 events]]\n[[Category:World War II orders of battle]]\n[[Category:United States Navy in World War II]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2018}}\n: ''For the Battle of Leyte Gulf, see [[Leyte Gulf order of battle]]''\n{{multiple image\n | direction = horizontal\n | width = 160\n | header = Theatre and fleet commanders<br>for the liberation of the Philippines\n | image1 = MacArthur_Manila.jpg\n | caption1 = Gen. Douglas MacArthur\n | image2 = Thomas_C._Kinkaid.jpg\n | caption2 = Vice Adm. Thomas C. Kinkaid\n}}\n\nOn 17 October 1944, troops of the [[Sixth United States Army|United States Sixth Army]] under the direct command of Lieutenant General [[Walter Krueger]], [[Battle of Leyte|invaded the Philippine island of Leyte]]. This operation was the beginning of General '''[[Douglas MacArthur]]''''s fulfillment of his [[Douglas MacArthur's escape from the Philippines|promise in March 1942]] to the Filipino people that he would liberate them from Japanese rule.\n\nMacArthur's formal title was Supreme Commander, Allied Forces, [[Pacific Ocean Areas (command)|Southwest Pacific Area]]. The amphibious landings were carried out and supported by the '''[[United States Seventh Fleet]]''', including 1 British and 11 Australian ships, under the direction of Vice Admiral '''[[Thomas C. Kinkaid]]'''.\n\n{{flagdeco|United States|1912}} '''Seventh Fleet'''\n* Combat ships: 18 [[escort carrier]]s, 6 old [[battleship#World War II|battleship]]s, 5 [[heavy cruiser]]s,{{efn|Two Australian}} 4 [[light cruiser]]s, 34 [[destroyer]]s,{{efn|Two Australian}} 17 [[destroyer escort]]s \n* 280+ amphibious landing and support ships{{efn|Three Australian}}\n* 110+ auxiliaries{{efn|Four Australian, one British}}\n\nIn case the [[Imperial Japanese Navy]] interfered, additional air cover was provided by the [[Fast Carrier Task Force|fast carriers]] of the [[United States Third Fleet|US Third Fleet]] under the command of Admiral '''[[William F. Halsey, Jr.]]'''.<br> \n{{flagdeco|United States|1912}} '''Third Fleet'''\n* 9 [[fleet carrier]]s, 8 [[light carrier]]s, 6 fast [[battleship#World War II|battleship]]s, 4 [[heavy cruiser]]s, 7 [[light cruiser]]s, 3 [[light cruiser#Atlanta-class cruiser|anti-aircraft light cruiser]]s, 58 [[destroyers]]\n\n== US Seventh Fleet ==\n{{multiple image\n | direction = horizontal\n | width = 200\n | header = \n | image1 = USS_Wasatch_(AGC-9).jpg\n | caption1 = Vice Adm. Kinkaid's flagship  ''Wasatch''\n | image2 = HMAS_Australia_(D84)_passing_through_the_Panama_Canal_in_March_1935.jpg\n | caption2 = Heavy cruiser HMAS ''Australia'' passing through the Panama Canal, 1935\n}}\n[[File:HMAS_Warramunga_AllanGreen.jpg|160px|thumb|Destroyer HMAS ''Warramunga'']]\nVice Admiral [[Thomas C. Kinkaid]] in amphibious command ship ''[[USS Wasatch|Wasatch]]''\n<!--[[File:USS_Nashville_(CL-43)_off_the_Mare_Island_Naval_Shipyard_on_4_August_1943.jpg|180px|thumb|Light cruiser ''Nashville'']]\n[[File:HMAS_Australia_(D84)_passing_through_the_Panama_Canal_in_March_1935.jpg|180px|thumb|Heavy cruiser ''Australia'' passing through the Panama Canal, 1935]]-->\n\n=== Combat Units ===\n\n==== Central Philippines Attack Force (Task Force 77) ====\nVice Admiral Kinkaid<br>\n: 1 light cruiser: ''[[USS Nashville (CL-43)|Nashville]]''\n: 4 destroyers (all [[Fletcher class destroyer|Fletcher-class]]): ''[[USS Ammen (DD-527)|Ammen]]'', ''[[USS Abner Read (DD-526)|Abner Read]]'', ''[[USS Mullany (DD-528)|Mullany]]'', ''[[USS Bush (DD-529)|Bush]]''\n\n===== Close Covering Group (Task Group 77.3) =====\nRear Admiral [[Russell S. Berkey]] \n: 2 heavy cruisers: {{flagdeco|Australia}} [[HMAS Australia (D84)|HMAS ''Australia'']], {{flagdeco|Australia}} [[HMAS Shropshire|HMAS ''Shropshire'']]\n: 2 light cruisers: ''[[USS Phoenix|Phoenix]]'', ''[[USS Boise|Boise]]''\n: 6 destroyers\n:: 4 [[Fletcher class destroyer|Fletcher-class]]: ''[[USS Bache (DD-470)|Bache]]'', ''[[USS Beale (DD-471)|Beale]]'', ''[[USS Daly|Daly]]'', ''[[USS Killen|Killen]]''\n:: 2 [[Tribal class destroyer (1936)|Tribal-class]]: {{flagdeco|Australia}} [[HMAS Arunta (I30)|HMAS ''Arunta'']], {{flagdeco|Australia}} [[HMAS Warramunga (I44)|HMAS ''Warramunga'']]\n\n===== Escort Carrier Group (Task Group 77.4) =====\n{{multiple image\n | direction = horizontal\n | width = 160\n | header = Taffy 1 Commander\n | image1 = Thomas_Lamison_Sprague.jpg\n | caption1 = Rear Adm. Thomas L. Sprague\n}}\n[[File:USS Suwannee (CVE-27) at anchor at Kwajalein atoll on 7 February 1944 (NH 106578).jpg|220px|thumb|Escort carrier ''Suwannee'']]\n\nRear Admiral [[Thomas L. Sprague]]\n\n'''\"Taffy 1\"'''<br>\n[[File:F4F-3_new_pitot_tube_of_later_model.jpg|220px|thumb|right|Grumman F4F Wildcat fighter]]\nRear Admiral Sprague\n: 6 escort carriers\n:: ''[[USS Sangamon (CVE-26)|Sangamon]]'' (Capts. M.E. Browder)\n::: ''Air Group 37'' (Lt. Cmdr. S.E. Hindman)\n::: 17 [[F6F Hellcat]] fighters\n::: &nbsp;&nbsp;9 [[TBM Avenger]] torpedo bombers\n:: ''[[USS Suwannee|Suwannee]]'' (Capt. W.D. Johnson)\n::: ''Air Group 60'' (Lt. Cmdr. H.O. Feilbach, USNR)\n::: 22 [[F6F Hellcat]] fighters\n::: &nbsp;&nbsp;9 [[TBM Avenger]] torpedo bombers\n:: ''[[USS Chenango 