rs\n::: VB-19: 30 [[SB2C Helldiver]] dive bombers\n::: VT-19: 18 [[TBM Avenger]] torpedo bombers\n\n:'''2 light carriers'''\n:: ''[[USS Princeton (CVL-23)|Princeton]]'' (Capt. W.H. Buracker)\n::: ''Air Group 27'' (Lt. Cmdr. F.A. Bardshar)\n::: VF-27: 21 [[F6F Hellcat]] fighters\n::: VT-27: &nbsp;&nbsp;9 [[TBM Avenger]] torpedo bombers\n:: ''[[USS Langley (CVL-27)|Langley]]'' (Capt. J.F. Wegforth)\n::: ''Air Group 44'' (Cmdr. M.T. Wordell)\n::: VF-44: 25 [[F6F Hellcat]] fighters\n::: VT-44: &nbsp;&nbsp;9 [[TBM Avenger]] torpedo bombers\n\n:'''4 fast [[battleship#World War II|battleships]]''' (Vice Admiral [[Willis Augustus Lee]]){{efn|Commander Battleships, Pacific Fleet}}\n::: ''[[USS Washington (BB-56)|Washington]]'' (Capt. T.R. Cooley)\n:: Battleship Division 8 (Rear Adm. Glenn B. Davis)\n::: ''[[USS Massachusetts (BB-59)|Massachusetts]]'' (Capt. W.W. Warlick)\n:: Battleship Division 9 (Rear Adm. Edward V. Hanson)\n::: ''[[USS Alabama (BB-60)|Alabama]]'' (Capt. V.R. Murphy), ''[[USS South Dakota (BB-57)|South Dakota]]'' (Capt. C.B. Momsen)\n\n:''' Cruiser Division 13''' (Rear Admiral Laurance T. DuBose)\n:: 3 light cruisers: ''[[USS Santa Fe (CL-60)|Santa Fe]]'' (Capt. Jerauld Wright), ''[[USS Mobile (CL-63)|Mobile]]'' (Capt. C.C. Miller), ''[[USS Birmingham (CL-62)|Birmingham]]'' (Capt. T.B. Inglis)\n:: 1 [[light cruiser#Atlanta-class cruiser|anti-aircraft light cruiser]]:{{efn|These cruisers were intended as destroyer leaders when designed. After the first two to be used in this role, ''[[USS Atlanta (CL-51)|Atlanta]]'' and ''[[USS Juneau (CL-52)|Juneau]]'', were lost at the [[Naval Battle of Guadalcanal]], this mission was abandoneded and the anti-aircraft mission adopted.<ref>Stille, p. 7.</ref>}} ''[[USS Reno (CL-96)|Reno]]'' (Capt. R.C. Alexander)\n\n:'''Screen''' (Capt. C.R. Todd)\n:: 14 destroyers (all [[Fletcher class destroyer|Fletcher-class]]): ''[[USS Clarence K. Bronson|Clarence K. Bronson]]'', ''[[USS Cotten|Cotten]]'', ''[[USS Dortch|Dortch]]'', ''[[USS Gatling|Gatling]]'', ''[[USS Healy (DD-672)|Healy]]'', ''[[USS Porterfield|Porterfield]]'', ''[[USS Callaghan (DD-792)|Callaghan]]'', ''[[USS Cassin Young|Cassin Young]]'', ''[[USS Irwin|Irwin]]'', ''[[USS Preston (DD-795)|Preston]]'', ''[[USS Laws|Laws]]'', ''[[USS Longshaw|Longshaw]]'', ''[[USS Morrison|Morrison]]'', ''[[USS Prichett|Prichett]]''\n\n==== Task Group 38.4 ====\n[[File:Ralph_E._Davison.jpg|140px|thumb|Rear Adm. Ralph E. Davison]]\n[[File:USS_Enterprise_%28CV-6%29_in_Puget_Sound%2C_September_1945.jpg|240px|thumb|Fleet carrier ''Enterprise'']]\n{{multiple image\n | direction = horizontal\n | width = 190\n | header = Destroyer ''Bagley'' \n | image1 = USS_Bagley_%28DD-386%29_before_World_War_II.jpg\n | caption1 = Before World War II\n | image2 = BagleyDD386.jpg\n | caption2 = After World War II\n}}\n\nRear Admiral Ralph E. Davison\n\n'''2 fleet carriers'''\n: ''[[USS Franklin (CV-13)|Franklin]]'' (Capt. J.M. Shoemaker)\n:: ''Air Group 13'' (Cmdr. R.L. Kibbe)\n:: VF-13: 34 [[F6F Hellcat]] fighters, 4 [[Grumman F6F Hellcat#Further development|F6F-xN Hellcat]] night fighters\n:: VB-13: 31 [[SB2C Helldiver]] dive bombers\n:: VT-13: 18 [[TBM Avenger]] torpedo bombers\n: ''[[USS Enterprise (CV-6)|Enterprise]]'' (Capt. Cato D. Glover)\n:: ''Air Group 20'' (Cmdr. D.F. Smith)\n:: VF-20: 35 [[F6F Hellcat]] fighters, 4 [[Grumman F6F Hellcat#Further development|F6F-xN Hellcat]] night fighters\n:: VB-20: 34 [[SB2C Helldiver]] dive bombers\n:: VT-20: 19 [[TBF Avenger]], 5 [[TBM Avenger]] torpedo bombers\n\n'''2 light carriers'''\n: ''[[USS San Jacinto (CVL-30)|San Jacinto]]'' (Capt. M.H. Kernodle)\n:: ''Air Group 51'' (Cmdr. C.L. Moore)\n:: VF-51: 19 [[F6F Hellcat]] fighters\n:: VT-51: &nbsp;&nbsp;7 [[TBM Avenger]] torpedo bombers\n: ''[[USS Belleau Wood (CVL-24)|Belleau Wood]]'' (Capts. John Perry)\n:: ''Air Group 21'' (Lt. Cmdr. V.F. Casey)\n:: VF-21: 25 [[F6F Hellcat]] fighters\n:: VT-21: &nbsp;&nbsp;9 [[TBM Avenger]] torpedo bombers\n\n: 1 heavy cruiser: ''[[USS New Orleans (CA-32)|New Orleans]]'' (Capt. J.E. Hurff)\n: 1 light cruiser: ''[[USS Biloxi|Biloxi]]'' (Capt. P.R. Heineman)\n\n'''Screen''' (Capt. V.D. Long)\n: 11 destroyers\n:: 3 [[Gleaves class destroyer|Gleaves-class]]: [[USS Wilkes (DD-441)|''Wilkes'']], [[USS Nicholson (DD-442)|''Nicholson'']], [[USS Swanson|''Swanson'']]\n:: 3 [[Gridley class destroyer|Gridley-class]]: [[USS Gridley (DD-380)|''Gridley'']], [[USS McCall (DD-400)|''McCall'']], [[USS Maury (DD-401)|''Maury'']]\n:: 5 [[Bagley class destroyer|Bagley-class]]: [[USS Bagley (DD-386)|''Bagley'']], [[USS Helm (DD-388)|''Helm'']], [[USS Mugford (DD-389)|''Mugford'']], [[USS Patterson (DD-392)|''Patterson'']], [[USS Ralph Talbot (DD-390)|''Ralph Talbot'']]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n*{{cite book\n | last      = Morison\n | first     = Samuel Eliot\n | year      = 1958 \n | title     = Leyte, June 1944 - January 1945\n | volume    = XII\n | series    = History of United States Naval Operations in World War II\n | publisher = Little, Brown and Co.\n | location  = Boston\n | isbn      = 0-7858-1313-6}}\n*{{cite book\n | last      = Stille\n | first     = Mark\n | year      = 2016\n | title     = US Navy Light Cruisers, 1941-45\n | publisher = Osprey Publishing, Ltd. \n | location  = Oxford\n | isbn      = 978-1-4728-1140-0}}\n\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1944]]\n[[Category:Pacific Ocean theatre of World War II]]\n[[Category:Naval aviation operations and battles]]\n[[Category:Battle of Leyte Gulf]]\n[[Category:Naval battles of World War II involving Japan]]\n[[Category:Naval battles of World War II involving the United States]]\n[[Category:October 1944 events]]\n[[Category:World War II orders of battle]]\n[[Category:United States Navy in World War II]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:Farragut class destroyer\u2192Farragut-class destroyer (1934),oiler\u2192Replenishment oiler,John S. McCain\u2192John S. McCain Sr.,South Dakota-class battleship\u2192South Dakota-class battleship (1939)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Invasion_of_Leyte_naval_order_of_battle"}
{"title_page": "LMS Stanier Class 5 4-6-0 4806", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2015}}\n{{more citations needed|date=December 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox locomotive\n| name             = LMS 4806\n| powertype        = Steam\n| image            = 44806 Llangollen Station (1).jpg\n| alt              = \n| caption          = 44806 Running around its train at Llangollen. \n| designer         = [[William Stanier]]\n| builder          = [[Derby Works]]\n| ordernumber      = \n| serialnumber     = 154 (second series)\n| buildmodel       = \n| builddate        = July 1944\n| whytetype        = [[4-6-0]]\n| uicclass         = \n| gauge            = {{track gauge|ussg}}\n| leadingdiameter  = {{convert|3|ft|3+1/2|in|m|3|abbr=on}}\n| driverdiameter   = {{convert|6|ft|0|in|m|3|abbr=on}}\n| length           = {{convert|63|ft|7+3/4|in|m|2|abbr=on}}\n| locoweight       = {{convert|72.20|LT|t ST|abbr=on}}\n| fueltype         = Coal\n| fuelcap          = {{convert|9|LT|t ST|1|abbr=on}}\n| watercap         = {{convert|4000|impgal|abbr=on}}\n| boiler           = LMS type 3C\n| boilerpressure   = {{convert|225|lbf/in2|MPa|2|abbr=on|lk=on}}\n| firearea         = {{convert|28+1/2|sqft|abbr=on}}\n| tubesandflues    = \n| fireboxarea      = \n| superheaterarea  =\n| cylindercount    = Two, outside \n| cylindersize     = {{convert|18+1/2|x|28|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| valvegear        = [[Walschaerts valve gear|Walschaerts]]\n| valvetype        = Piston valves\n| tractiveeffort   = {{convert|25455|lbf|kN|2|abbr=on|lk=on}}\n| operator         = {{unbulleted list|[[London, Midland and Scottish Railway]]|\u2192 [[British Railways]]}}\n| powerclass       = {{unbulleted list|LMS: 5P5F|BR: 5MT}}\n| axleloadclass    = BR: [[Route Availability]] 7\n| fleetnumbers     = \n| withdrawndate    = August 1968\n| restoredate      = \n| currentowner     = [[North Yorkshire Moors Railway]]\n| disposition      = Awaiting Overhaul\n}}\n\n'''[[LMS Stanier Class 5 4-6-0]] No. 44806''' is a preserved British [[steam locomotive]]. It was built at [[Derby Works|Derby]] in 1944.<!-- works number?-->\n\n== Service history ==\nOriginally numbered 4806 by the LMS, it had 40000 added to its number under [[British Railways]] after nationalisation in 1948. 44806 was one of the last locomotives to be withdrawn from service, surviving until 1968, the last year of [[Steam locomotives of British Railways#Withdrawal|steam on British Railways]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" |\n|-\n|+Shed allocations <ref name=\"Llangollen 44806\" />\n|-\n! Location !! Shed code !! From\n|-\n| Toton \n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 18A || 15 July 1944\n|-\n| Leicester \n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 15C || 28 April 1948\n|-\n| Nottingham  \n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 16A || 9 December 1956\n|-\n| Kentish Town  \n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 14B || 15 December 1956\n|-\n| Nottingham  \n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 16A || 18 October 1957\n|-\n| Burton  \n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 17B || 12 July 1964\n|-\n| Speke Junction  \n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 8C || 26 June 1967\n|-\n| [[Lostock Hall]] \n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 10D || 30 March 1968\n|}\n\n== Preservation ==\n[[File:Black Five 44806 approaching Newby Bridge, 1973.jpg|thumb|left|Approaching [[Newby Bridge]] in 1973]]\n44806 was an early candidate for preservation, moving directly from BR to the \"[[Steamtown (Carnforth)|Steamtown]]\" collection at [[Carnforth]], where it was housed in the same locomotive depot where steam's final fires had been dropped only recently. This meant that it was not subjected to the years of neglect and parts-stripping at [[Woodham Brothers]] [[scrapyard]] in [[Barry, Vale of Glamorgan]], [[South Wales]] which was the fate of many.\n\nIn preservation, it was unusually well-travelled between museums and lines, although staying in the North West of England. Some years were spent based in [[Accrington]], with working excursions to a planned preserved line at [[Helmshore]]. Although these exact plans never quite came to fruition after that station's closure in 1972, most of the line survived as what is now the [[East Lancashire Railway]].<ref name=\"East Lancs railway\" >{{cite web\n  |title=A History of the East Lancashire Railway\n  |url=http://east-lancs-rly.co.uk/?p=history&m=43\n  |publisher=[http://east-lancs-rly.co.uk East Lancashire Railway]\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 1973, 44806 was based for a short time at the newly reopened [[Lakeside and Haverthwaite Railway]], as their largest and only tender engine, but operating a large tender engine was difficult on a line without a turntable. Whilst at Haverthwaite, 44806 was adopted by the ITV children's TV series [[Magpie (TV series)|Magpie]] and named \"Magpie\". The Magpie programme was always in competition with the BBC's comparable [[Blue Peter]] programme, which had earlier adopted the LNER A2 Peppercorn [[Blue Peter (locomotive)|532 Blue Peter]], conveniently built under that name.\n\nShortly after this, a crack was found in the boiler of 44806, in the outer [[Firebox (steam engine)|firebox]]. Haverthwaite did not have the workshop facilities for an engine of this length or weight, so it was moved, this time to \"Steamport\" in [[Southport]]. These were busy times for the British steam preservation movement, with many new projects and scrapyard rescues all competing for attention, time and money. As a result, 'Magpie' languished. In 1983, Magpie was moved to Manchester and the [[Museum of Science and Industry in Manchester|Museum of Science and Industry]], as a purely static exhibit.\n\n=== Return to steam ===\nIn 1993, 44806, with its 20-year-old firebox crack, travelled to the [[Llangollen Railway]],<ref name=\"Llangollen\" >{{cite web\n  |url=http://llangollenrail.llangollen-railway.co.uk/steamlocoinfo.html\n  |title=Llangollen Railway\n  |publisher=[http://www.llangollen-railway.co.uk Llangollen Railway]\n  |access-date=1 May 2008\n  |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080321194424/http://llangollenrail.llangollen-railway.co.uk/steamlocoinfo.html\n  |archive-date=21 March 2008\n  |url-status=dead\n  }}</ref> where repair work began. This work took almost three years to complete, with a return to steam on 15 September 1995.<ref name=\"Llangollen 44806\" /> It worked on the Llangollen for nearly ten years, first back as 4806 in black LMS livery with red lining, then once again as 44806, wearing the BR ''\"ferret and a dartboard\"'' tender badges with red and white lining.\n\n=== Return to steam again ===\n[[File:Black Five 44806 Kenneth Aldcroft, nameplate, Llangollen 2010.jpg|thumb|''Kenneth Aldcroft'' nameplate]]\nThe expiration of the locomotive's 10-year boiler certificate prompted another rebuild. The work this time was less serious, being mostly wear items such as boiler tubes, firebox stays and worn tyres. The work was completed successfully and 4806 returned to steam on 29 August 2007 and was back in service on 14 September.<ref name=\"Llangollen 44806\" >{{cite web\n  |url=http://llanrailarchive.llangollen-railway.co.uk/sloco44806.html\n  |title=44806 Magpie history\n  |access-date=1 May 2008\n  |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080724160532/http://llanrailarchive.llangollen-railway.co.uk/sloco44806.html\n  |archive-date=24 July 2008\n  |url-status=dead\n  }} (many photographs)</ref> The new livery was again BR period, but this time in unlined gloss black.\n\nSince its initial preservation, 44806 had been privately owned by one man, Ken Aldcroft. Aldcroft died in 2003, and 44806 passed to his daughter Ms Renee Wyatt. To commemorate Aldcroft's 35 years of preservation (he owned 44806 for ten years more than the original owners), 44806 was renamed ''Kenneth Aldcroft''.\n\n== Current status ==\n[[File:Black Five 44806, platform, Llangollen 2010.jpg|thumb|[[Llangollen railway station|Llangollen]] station in 2010]]\n44806 ''Kenneth Aldcroft'' was based and working at the [[Llangollen Railway]].<ref name=\"Llangollen\" /> 2008 was the 40th anniversary of [[Steam locomotives of British Railways#Withdrawal|the end of British Railways steam]], and of 44806's own preservation.\nIn July 2013, the locomotive was offered for sale, and was purchased by the [[List of rolling stock preserved on the North Yorkshire Moors Railway#Steam locomotives 2|North Yorkshire Moors Railway]].\n\nUntil January 2018 when its then boiler certificate expired 44806 operated trains on the NYMR only between Grosmont and Pickering because it did not have mainline equipment fitted. It is planned to be certified to run trains to Whitby after completion of its next overhaul. As of August 2018, the engine is in storage awaiting overhaul.\n\nIn February 2020 no 44806 was sold from the NYMR to Peter Best and the overhaul is now underway to return the engine to operational condition. On completion of its present overhaul the engine will remain at the NYMR for use on their regular passenger trains. The engine will also become part of the NYMR based fleet of engines which is approved to run between Grosmont, Whitby and Battersby as its owner intends to operate the engine on the mainline. However, it will not venture onto the mainline beyond Battersby.<ref>https://www.railadvent.co.uk/2020/02/new-owner-for-black-5-steam-locomotive-44806.html New Owner for 44806</ref>\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nFile:Langley Mill Up fast freight at Stoneyford Junction geograph-2765887-by-Ben-Brooksbank.jpg|44806 making her way down the goods line with a class C goods train near Langley Mill in July 1963.\nFile:East Lancashire Railway at Helmshore station 1970 from Helmshore Road.jpg|44806 Passing Helmshore signal box while on her way to the [[Lakeside and Haverthwaite Railway]].\nFile:LMS Class 5 No 44806 (8063191468).jpg|44806 Resting on Llangollen shed waiting for its next duty\nFile:44806 at Carrog Station (1).jpg|44806 Running round its train at Carrog.\nFile:44806 at Carrog Station (3).jpg|44806 Arriving into Carrog with a demonstration freight train in April 2011.\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n{{Commons category|LMS Stanier Class 5 4-6-0 4806}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lms Stanier Class 5 4-6-0 4806}}\n[[Category:LMS Stanier Class 5 4-6-0|44806]]\n[[Category:Preserved London, Midland and Scottish Railway steam locomotives]]\n[[Category:Llangollen Railway|44806]]\n[[Category:Individual locomotives of Great Britain]]\n[[Category:Railway locomotives introduced in 1944]]\n[[Category:Standard gauge steam locomotives of Great Britain]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2015}}\n{{more citations needed|date=December 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox locomotive\n| name             = LMS 4806\n| powertype        = Steam\n| image            = 44806 Llangollen Station (1).jpg\n| alt              = \n| caption          = 44806 Running around its train at Llangollen. \n| designer         = [[William Stanier]]\n| builder          = [[Derby Works]]\n| ordernumber      = \n| serialnumber     = 154 (second series)\n| buildmodel       = \n| builddate        = July 1944\n| whytetype        = [[4-6-0]]\n| uicclass         = \n| gauge            = {{track gauge|ussg}}\n| leadingdiameter  = {{convert|3|ft|3+1/2|in|m|3|abbr=on}}\n| driverdiameter   = {{convert|6|ft|0|in|m|3|abbr=on}}\n| length           = {{convert|63|ft|7+3/4|in|m|2|abbr=on}}\n| locoweight       = {{convert|72.20|LT|t ST|abbr=on}}\n| fueltype         = Coal\n| fuelcap          = {{convert|9|LT|t ST|1|abbr=on}}\n| watercap         = {{convert|4000|impgal|abbr=on}}\n| boiler           = LMS type 3C\n| boilerpressure   = {{convert|225|lbf/in2|MPa|2|abbr=on|lk=on}}\n| firearea         = {{convert|28+1/2|sqft|abbr=on}}\n| tubesandflues    = \n| fireboxarea      = \n| superheaterarea  =\n| cylindercount    = Two, outside \n| cylindersize     = {{convert|18+1/2|x|28|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n| valvegear        = [[Walschaerts valve gear|Walschaerts]]\n| valvetype        = Piston valves\n| tractiveeffort