Gloucestershire County Council|Gloucestershire]]&nbsp;\u2020 || style=\"background: #fff7f7\" | ''a'')&nbsp;[[Gloucester]], ''b'')&nbsp;[[Tewkesbury (borough)|Tewkesbury]], ''c'')&nbsp;[[Cheltenham]], ''d'')&nbsp;[[Cotswold (district)|Cotswold]], ''e'')&nbsp;[[Stroud (district)|Stroud]], ''f'')&nbsp;[[Forest of Dean (district)|Forest of Dean]]\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\" | [[Wiltshire]] || colspan=\"2\" style=\"background: #eeffeb\" | '''6'''.&nbsp;[[Swindon (borough)|Swindon]] U.A.\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background: #eeffeb\" | '''7'''.&nbsp;[[Wiltshire Council|Wiltshire U.A.]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Dorset]]|| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background: #eeffeb\" | '''8'''.&nbsp;[[Dorset (unitary authority)|Dorset&nbsp;]]U.A.\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background: #eeffeb\" | '''9'''.&nbsp;[[Bournemouth, Christchurch and Poole]] U.A.\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |[[Devon]]|| style=\"background: #fff1f1\" |'''11'''.&nbsp;[[Devon County Council|Devon&nbsp;\u2020]]|| style=\"background: #fff7f7\" |''a'')&nbsp;[[Exeter]], ''b'')&nbsp;[[East Devon]], ''c'')&nbsp;[[Mid Devon]], ''d'')&nbsp;[[North Devon]], ''e'')&nbsp;[[Torridge District|Torridge]], ''f'')&nbsp;[[West Devon]], ''g'')&nbsp;[[South Hams]], ''h'')&nbsp;[[Teignbridge]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background: #eeffeb\" |'''12'''.&nbsp;[[Torbay]] U.A.\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background: #eeffeb\" | '''14'''.&nbsp;[[Plymouth]] U.A.\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\" | [[Cornwall]] || colspan=\"2\" style=\"background: #eeffeb\" | '''15'''.&nbsp;[[Isles of Scilly]] ''sui generis'' U.A.\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background: #eeffeb\" | '''13'''.&nbsp;[[Cornwall Council|Cornwall U.A.]]\n|- style=\"border-top: 3px solid black\"\n| rowspan=\"8\" align=\"center\" |'''[[West Midlands (region)|West Midlands]]'''<br />[[File:West Midlands counties 2009 map.svg|250px]] || colspan=\"3\" style=\"background: #eeffeb\" | '''1'''.&nbsp;[[Herefordshire]] U.A.\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Shropshire]] || colspan=\"2\" style=\"background: #eeffeb\" | '''2'''.&nbsp;[[Shropshire Council|Shropshire]] U.A.\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background: #eeffeb\" | '''3'''.&nbsp;[[Telford and Wrekin]] U.A.\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Staffordshire]] || style=\"background: #fff1f1\" | '''4'''.&nbsp;[[Staffordshire County Council|Staffordshire]]&nbsp;\u2020 || style=\"background: #fff7f7\" | ''a'')&nbsp;[[Cannock Chase (district)|Cannock Chase]], ''b'')&nbsp;[[East Staffordshire]], ''c'')&nbsp;[[Lichfield (district)|Lichfield]], ''d'')&nbsp;[[Newcastle-under-Lyme (borough)|Newcastle-under-Lyme]], ''e'')&nbsp;[[South Staffordshire]],  ''f'')&nbsp;[[Stafford (borough)|Stafford]], ''g'')&nbsp;[[Staffordshire Moorlands]], ''h'')&nbsp;[[Borough of Tamworth|Tamworth]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background: #eeffeb\" | '''5'''.&nbsp;[[Stoke-on-Trent]] U.A.\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background: #fff1f1\" | '''6'''.&nbsp;[[Warwickshire]]&nbsp;\u2020 || style=\"background: #fff7f7\" | ''a'')&nbsp;[[North Warwickshire]], ''b'')&nbsp;[[Nuneaton and Bedworth]], ''c'')&nbsp;[[Rugby (borough)|Rugby]], ''d'')&nbsp;[[Stratford-on-Avon (district)|Stratford-on-Avon]], ''e'')&nbsp;[[Warwick (district)|Warwick]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background: #e1f7ff\" | '''7'''.&nbsp;[[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]]&nbsp;* || style=\"background: #f1fbff\" | ''a'')&nbsp;[[Birmingham]], ''b'')&nbsp;[[Coventry]], ''c'')&nbsp;[[Dudley (borough)|Dudley]], ''d'')&nbsp;[[Sandwell (borough)|Sandwell]], ''e'')&nbsp;[[Solihull (borough)|Solihull]], ''f'')&nbsp;[[Walsall (borough)|Walsall]], ''g'')&nbsp;[[Wolverhampton]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background: #fff1f1\" | '''8'''.&nbsp;[[Worcestershire]]&nbsp;\u2020 || style=\"background: #fff7f7\" | ''a'')&nbsp;[[Bromsgrove (district)|Bromsgrove]], ''b'')&nbsp;[[Malvern Hills (district)|Malvern Hills]], ''c'')&nbsp;[[Redditch]], ''d'')&nbsp;[[Worcester]], ''e'')&nbsp;[[Wychavon]], ''f'')&nbsp;[[Wyre Forest (district)|Wyre Forest]]\n|- style=\"border-top: 3px solid black\"\n| rowspan=\"8\" align=\"center\" |'''[[Yorkshire and the Humber]]'''<br />[[File:Yorkshire and the Humber counties 2009 map.svg|250px]] || colspan=\"2\" style=\"background: #e1f7ff\" | '''1'''.&nbsp;[[South Yorkshire]]&nbsp;* || style=\"background: #f1fbff\" | ''a'')&nbsp;[[Sheffield]], ''b'')&nbsp;[[Metropolitan Borough of Rotherham|Rotherham]], ''c'')&nbsp;[[Metropolitan Borough of Barnsley|Barnsley]], ''d'')&nbsp;[[Metropolitan Borough of Doncaster|Doncaster]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background: #e1f7ff\" | '''2'''.&nbsp;[[West Yorkshire]]&nbsp;* || style=\"background: #f1fbff\" | ''a'')&nbsp;[[City of Wakefield|Wakefield]], ''b'')&nbsp;[[Kirklees]], ''c'')&nbsp;[[Calderdale]], ''d'')&nbsp;[[City of Bradford|Bradford]], ''e'')&nbsp;[[City of Leeds|Leeds]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[North Yorkshire]]<br /><small>(part only)</small> || style=\"background: #fff1f1\" | '''3'''.&nbsp;[[North Yorkshire County Council|North Yorkshire]]&nbsp;\u2020 || style=\"background: #fff7f7\" | ''a'')&nbsp;[[Selby (district)|Selby]], ''b'')&nbsp;[[Harrogate (borough)|Harrogate]], ''c'')&nbsp;[[Craven]], ''d'')&nbsp;[[Richmondshire]], ''e'')&nbsp;[[Hambleton District|Hambleton]], ''f'')&nbsp;[[Ryedale]], ''g'')&nbsp;[[Scarborough (borough)|Scarborough]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background: #eeffeb\"| '''4'''.&nbsp;[[York]] U.A.\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[East Riding of Yorkshire]] || colspan=\"2\" style=\"background: #eeffeb\"| '''5'''.&nbsp;[[East Riding of Yorkshire Council|East Riding of Yorkshire U.A.]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background: #eeffeb\"| '''6'''.&nbsp;[[Kingston upon Hull]] U.A.\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Lincolnshire]]<br /><small>(part only)</small> || colspan=\"2\" style=\"background: #eeffeb\"| '''7'''.&nbsp;[[North Lincolnshire]] U.A.\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background: #eeffeb\"| '''8'''.&nbsp;[[North East Lincolnshire]] U.A.\n|- style=\"border-top: 3px solid black\"\n| rowspan=\"4\" |  || colspan=\"2\" | {{legend|#fff1f1|\u2020 [[non-metropolitan county]]|outline=silver}}&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<small>(all two-tier except for Berkshire)</small> || {{legend|#fff7f7|[[non-metropolitan district]]|outline=silver}} \n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" | {{legend|#eeffeb|U.A. [[unitary authorities of England|unitary authority]] (non-metropolitan county and district)|outline=silver}} &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<small>(except for Berkshire districts which are not counties)</small><br />\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" | {{legend|#e1f7ff|* [[metropolitan county]]|outline=silver}} || {{legend|#f1fbff|[[metropolitan district]]|outline=silver}}\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" | {{legend|#fffdf5|[[List of London boroughs|Local government district in London]] (the [[London borough]]s and [[City of London]])|outline=silver}}\n|-\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Combined authority]]\n*[[List of English counties leaders]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Refbegin}}\n*{{note|county 1|C1}}&nbsp; Also a ceremonial county of identical area.\n*{{note|county 2|C2}}&nbsp; Also a ceremonial county covering a larger area.\n*{{note|county 3|C3}}&nbsp; Cumbria, Hertfordshire, Norfolk, Northamptonshire, Oxfordshire, Suffolk, Surrey, Warwickshire, West Sussex and Worcestershire occupy the same area as the ceremonial county; Buckinghamshire, Cambridgeshire, Derbyshire, Devon, Dorset, East Sussex, Essex, Gloucestershire, Hampshire, Kent, Lancashire, Leicestershire, Lincolnshire, North Yorkshire, Nottinghamshire, Somerset and Staffordshire are larger for ceremonial purposes, being combined with one or more unitary authorities.\n*{{note|district 1|D1}}&nbsp; Metropolitan (36); non-metropolitan two-tier (192); unitary authority (55); London borough (32); sui generis (2).\n*{{note|no council|NC}}&nbsp; Berkshire has no county council and the districts function as unitary authorities.\n{{Refend}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/guide-method/geography/beginner-s-guide/administrative/england/counties--non-metropolitan-districts-and-unitary-authorities/map-of-the-uk-counties-and-unitary-administrations.pdf Map of the UK counties and unitary administrations] \n*[http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/guide-method/geography/beginner-s-guide/administrative/england/counties--non-metropolitan-districts-and-unitary-authorities/map-of-all-uk-local-authorities.pdf Map of all UK local authorities]\n\n{{Subdivisions of England}}\n{{Administrative geography of the United Kingdom}}\n\n[[Category:Subdivisions of England| ]]\n[[Category:Local government in England| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox subdivision type\n| name = Subdivisions of England\n| map = [[File:England Administrative 2010.png|300px|Administrative map of England (2010)]]<br/>Subdivisions of England (as of 2019) that have a principal local authority: two-tier [[Non-metropolitan county|non-metropolitan counties]] and their [[non-metropolitan district]]s; [[metropolitan borough]]s; [[Unitary authorities of England|unitary authorities]]; [[London borough]]s; and the ''sui generis'' [[City of London]] and [[Isles of Scilly]].\n| territory =[[England]]\n| subdivision =\n {{Infobox |class=nowrap |bodystyle={{infobox subbox bodystyle}};width:auto;\n  |labelstyle=font-weight:normal;white-space:nowrap; |datastyle=text-align:right;\n  |label1=''Type'' |data1=''Number''\n  |label2=[[Regions of England|Region]] |data2=9\n  |label3=[[Ceremonial counties of England|Ceremonial county]] |data3=48\n  |label4=[[Metropolitan and non-metropolitan counties of England|Metropolitan county]] |data4=6\n  |label5=[[Metropolitan and non-metropolitan counties of England|Non-metropolitan county]] |data5=77\n  |label6={{lower|0.1em|[[Districts of England|District]]}} |data6=326{{ref|district 1|D1}}\n  |label7=[[Civil parishes in England|Civil parish]] |data7=[[Approximation|~]]4,500\n }}\n}}\n{{Politics of England}}\n\nThe '''subdivisions of [[England]]''' constitute a hierarchy of [[administrative division]]s and non-administrative ceremonial areas.\n\nOverall, England is divided into [[Regions of England|nine regions]] and [[Ceremonial counties of England|48 ceremonial counties]], although these have only a limited role in public policy. For the purposes of [[Local government in England|local government]], the country is divided into [[Counties of England|counties]], [[Districts of England|districts]] and [[Civil parishes of England|parishes]]. In some areas, counties and districts form a two-tier administrative structure, while in others they are combined under a [[unitary authority]]. Parishes cover only part of England.\n\nThe current system is the result of incremental reform which has its origins in legislation enacted in 1965 and [[Local Government Act 1972|1972]].<ref name=\"Jones\">Jones, B., Kavanagh, D., Moran, M. & Norton, P., Politics UK, (2004), Pearson Longman.</ref>\n\n== Regions ==\n{{main|Regions of England}}\n\n{{England Labelled Map|200px|float=left|Londonprefix = Greater|WMsuffix = (region)}}\nAt the highest level, all of England is divided into nine regions that are each made up of a number of counties and districts. These 'government office regions' were created in 1994,<ref name=\"Atkinson\"/> and since the [[1999 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|1999 Euro-elections]], they have been used as the [[European Parliament constituencies in the United Kingdom]] and in England's [[European Parliament]] constituencies.\n\nThe regions vary greatly in their areas covered, populations and contributions to the national economy.<ref name=\"Atkinson\" /> All have the same status, except [[Greater London|London]] which has substantive [[devolution|devolved powers]].<ref name=\"Guide London\">Collins, S., Colville, I & Pengelly, S., A Guide to the Greater London Authority, (2000), Sweet and Maxwell</ref>\n\nThere was a failed attempt to create [[2004 Northern England devolution referendums|elected regional assemblies]] outside London in 2004 and since then the structures of regional governance ([[Regional assembly (England)|regional assemblies]], [[Regional development agency|regional development agencies]] and [[local authority leaders' board]]s) have been subject to review.  Following the change of government in 2010, these were scheduled for abolition by 2012<!-- at the latest-->.{{Update inline|date=March 2014}}\n\n== Counties and districts ==\n{{main|Counties of England|Districts of England}}\n\n[[File:English regions and counties by type 2019.jpg|alt=|thumb|364x364px|{{Legend-line|3px solid #646464|[[Regions of England|regional]] boundary}}\n{{Legend-line|2px solid #646464|[[Ceremonial counties of England|ceremonial county]] boundary}}\n{{Legend-line|1px solid #00c852|unitary authority boundary}}\n{{Legend|#ffd0d0|two-tier [[non-metropolitan county]]|outline=#A0A0A0}}\n{{Legend|#cefef2|[[metropolitan county]]|outline=#A0A0A0}}\n{{Legend|#f8a20c|[[Greater London]] (including [[City of London]])|outline=#A0A0A0}}\n{{Legend|#3ce67b|[[Unitary authorities of England|unitary authority]] (non-metropolitan county)|outline=#00c852}}]]\nFor non-administrative purposes, England is wholly divided into 48 counties,<ref name=\"LA 1997\"/> commonly known, but not named in statute, as [[Ceremonial counties of England|ceremonial counties]]. These counties are used for the purposes of appointing [[Lord Lieutenant|Lords Lieutenant]]<ref name=\"LA 1997\"/> who are historically the Crown's representatives in those areas. Ceremonial counties are often different from the metropolitan and non-metropolitan counties used for local government as they include the areas covered by unitary authorities. They are taken into consideration when drawing up Parliamentary constituency boundaries.\n\nFor local government, England is divided into areas with a two-tier structure of counties and districts governed by two local authorities, and unitary authority areas where there is one local authority. The arrangement varies in different parts of the country and there are four main configurations: non-metropolitan two-tier 'shire' areas, six metropolitan counties, unitary authorities, and Greater London.\n\n===Two-tier non-metropolitan counties===\nMost of the geographical area of England is within a two-tier non-metropolitan arrangement. In 25 of these areas the [[county council]]s provide the majority of services, including education and social services, and the 188 district councils have a more limited role.<ref name=\"Jones\"/> Non-metropolitan districts can additionally have the status of borough or city, although this has no effect on their powers or functions. All two-tier non-metropolitan counties are also ceremonial counties.{{ref|county 3|C3}} [[Berkshire]] is an anomaly in this arrangement whereby its districts are unitary authorities, but the non-metropolitan county was not formally abolished<ref name=\"Berks 1996\"/> and it is also a ceremonial county.<ref name=\"LA 1997\">{{cite web | url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1997/23/contents/made | title=Lieutenancies Act 1997 | publisher=Office of Public Sector Information | year=1997 | accessdate=8 August 2010 }}</ref> [[Bedfordshire]] and [[Cheshire]] are two former non-metropolitan counties that continue to exist only as ceremonial counties.\n\n===Metropolitan counties===\n\nSix large conurbations of England correspond to [[Metropolitan county|metropolitan counties]].<ref name=\"Jones\"/> Each metropolitan county had a county council providing limited strategic services, such as public transport and planning, from 1974 to 1986.<ref name=\"Jones\"/> Despite no longer having county councils the metropolitan counties still legally exist, and are each a ceremonial county. County-level functions, such as public transport, are exercised by joint-boards and other arrangements organised by the district councils. In the metropolitan counties, the 36 district councils operate effectively as unitary authorities and provide the majority of services, including education and social services.<ref name=\"Atkinson\">{{ cite book |author1=Atkinson, H.  |author2=Wilks-Heeg, S.  |lastauthoramp=yes | title=Local Government from Thatcher to Blair | year=2000 | publisher=Polity}}</ref> All metropolitan districts additionally have the status of borough, and some are cities, although this has no effect on their powers or functions. From April 2011 there has been a formal upper-tier structure in Greater Manchester with the creation of the [[Greater Manchester Combined Authority]].<ref name=\"GMCA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.agma.gov.uk/cms_media/files/greater_manchester_combined_authority_final_scheme.pdf|publisher=agma.gov.uk|author=Association of Greater Manchester Authorities|authorlink=Association of Greater Manchester Authorities|date=March 2010|accessdate=9 August 2010|format=PDF|title=Greater Manchester Combined Authority Final Scheme}}</ref>\n\n===London===\nThe [[Greater London]] administrative area created in 1965 corresponds to the London region. Through incremental change, culminating in 2000, the upper-tier authority is the [[Greater London Authority]], comprising an elected [[Mayor of London]] and the [[London Assembly]].<ref name=\"Travers\">Travers, T., The Politics of London, (2004), Palgrave</ref> Greater London is divided into 32 [[London borough]]s, also dating from 1965, each governed by a London borough council. The ancient [[City of London]] forms a 33rd division and is governed by the [[City of London Corporation]], a ''sui generis'' authority unlike any other in England<ref name=\"Travers\"/> that has largely avoided any of the reforms of local government in the 19th and 20th centuries.<ref name=\"Hebbert\">{{ cite book | title= London: More by fortune than design | publisher=John Wiley & Sons | first=Michael | last=Hebbert | year= 1998}}</ref> The City of London, and the rest of Greater London, each form a ceremonial county. The London borough councils and the City of London Corporation provide the majority of services, for example they are education authorities and co-ordinate waste management, whereas the Greater London Authority is responsible for the key strategic services of public transport, the police, economic development and emergency planning.<ref name=\"Travers\"/>\n\n===Unitary authorities===\n{{main|Unitary authorities of England}}\nOutside London and the metropolitan counties, some parts of England are governed by a single council, commonly called (but not named in statute) as a unitary authority.<ref name=\"Jones\"/> Unitary authorities are a combined non-metropolitan county and non-metropolitan district, undertaking the functions of both.<ref name=\"1992 Act\">{{ cite web | url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1992/19/contents/made| title=Local Government Act 1992 | year=1992 | publisher=Office of Public Sector Information | accessdate=8 August 2010 }}</ref> Unitary authorities can additionally have the status of [[Borough status in the United Kingdom|borough]] or [[City status in the United Kingdom|city]], although this has no effect on their powers or functions.\n\n46 unitary authorities were [[Local Government Commission for England (1992)|created between 1995 and 1998]] and nine more were [[2009 structural changes to local government in England|created in 2009]], followed by further changes in [[2019 structural changes to local government in England|2019]] and 2020. They were formed either by non-metropolitan districts taking on county-level functions, or by counties taking on district-level functions. In some cases, borders were altered or districts were combined during this reorganisation. [[Berkshire]] is an anomaly in this arrangement whereby its districts became unitary authorities, but the non-metropolitan county was not formally abolished.<ref name=\"Berks 1996\">{{cite web | url= http://www.legislaton.gov.uk/uksi/1996/1879/contents/made | year=1996 | title=The Berkshire (Structural Change) Order 1996 | accessdate= 13 September 2012 | publisher=National Archives(legislation.gov.uk) }}</ref>\n\nFor ceremonial purposes, unitary authorities are considered to be part of the county to which they formerly belonged.  Politically, however, they are fully independent entities, unaffiliated with the council of their former county.  For instance, the unitary authority of [[Plymouth]] is traditionally considered part of [[Devon]], though politically it is not part of the county.  In the case of [[Berkshire]], there is no county council, as all of its former territory is now covered by six unitary authorities, unaffiliated with each other politically.  Although there is no county council in Berkshire, these six unitary authorities comprise the ceremonial county of Berkshire.\n\n===Isles of Scilly===\nThe [[Isles of Scilly]] are governed by a ''sui generis'' local authority called the [[Council of the Isles of Scilly]]. The authority was established in 1890 as the Isles of Scilly Rural District Council. It was renamed but otherwise unreformed by the changes in local government that occurred in 1974 in the rest of England outside Greater London.<ref name=\"1972 Act\">{{ cite web | url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1972/70/contents| title=Local Government Act 1972 | publisher=Office of Public Sector Information | year=1972 | accessdate= 9 August 2010 }}</ref> Although effectively a unitary authority, for example it is an education authority,<ref name=\"Scilly Education\">{{ cite web | url=http://www.scilly.gov.uk/education/ | publisher=Council of the Isles of Scilly | title=Education and Learning | date= | access-date=9 August 2010 | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090604165157/http://www.scilly.gov.uk/education/ | archive-date=4 June 2009 | df= }}</ref> the Isles of Scilly are part of the [[Cornwall]] ceremonial county and combine with [[Cornwall Council]] for services such as health<ref name=\"Cornwall PCT\">{{ cite web | url=http://www.cornwallandislesofscilly.nhs.uk/CornwallAndIslesOfScillyPCT/AboutUs/AboutUs.aspx | accessdate=9 August 2010 | title=About Us | publisher=Cornwall and Isles of Scilly Primary Care Trust }}</ref> and economic development.<ref name=\"Cornwall Partner\">{{ cite web | url=http://www.cornwall.gov.uk/default.aspx?page=24697 | title=The Cornwall and Isles of Scilly Enterprise Partnership | publisher=Cornwall Council | date=30 July 2010  | accessdate= 9 August 2010 }}</ref>\n\n== Civil parishes ==\n{{main|Civil parishes in England}}\n\nThe civil parish is the most local unit of government in England.<ref name=\"Jones\"/> A parish is governed by a [[Parish councils in England|parish council]] or [[parish meeting]], which exercises a limited number of functions that would otherwise be delivered by the local authority. There is one civil parish in Greater London ([[Queen's Park, London|Queen's Park]], in the [[City of Westminster]]),<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-18249803 |title=Queen's Park parish council gets go-ahead |accessdate=2 August 2014 |date=29 May 2012 |work=BBC News London }}</ref> and not all of the rest of England is parished. The number of parishes and total area parished is growing.\n\n== Lists of subdivisions ==\n\n===Regions===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Type !! Created !! Number !!width=\"100%\"| Units\n|-\n| [[Regions of England|Region]] || 1994 || 9 || \n{{div col|small=no|colwidth=22em}}\n*[[East of England]]\n*[[East Midlands]]\n*[[Greater London|London]]\n*[[North East England|North East]]\n*[[North West England|North West]]\n*[[South East England|South East]]\n*[[South West England|South West]]\n*[[West Midlands (region)|West Midlands]]\n*[[Yorkshire and the Humber]]\n{{div col end}}\n|}\n\n===Two-tier non-metropolitan counties===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Type || Created || Number ||width=\"100%\"| Units\n|-\n| [[Non-metropolitan county]] || 1974 || 25 || \n{{div col|small=no|colwidth=22em}}\n*[[Cambridgeshire]]\n*[[Cumbria]]\n*[[Derbyshire]]\n*[[Devon]]\n*[[East Sussex]]\n*[[Essex]]\n*[[Gloucestershire]]\n*[[Hampshire]]\n*[[Hertfordshire]]\n*[[Kent]]\n*[[Lancashire]]\n*[[Leicestershire]]\n*[[Lincolnshire]]\n*[[Norfolk]]\n*[[Northamptonshire]]\n*[[North Yorkshire]]\n*[[Nottinghamshire]]\n*[[Oxfordshire]]\n*[[Somerset]]\n*[[Staffordshire]]\n*[[Suffolk]]\n*[[Surrey]]\n*[[Warwickshire]]\n*[[West Sussex]]\n*[[Worcestershire]]\n{{div col end}}\n|-\n| [[Non-metropolitan district]] || 1974 || 192 || ''[[Non-metropolitan district#List of counties and districts|List of districts]]''\n|}\n\n===Metropolitan counties===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Type || Created || Number ||colspan=\"6\" width=\"100%\"| Units\n|-\n| [[Metropolitan county]] || 1974 || 6 || [[Greater Manchester]] || [[Merseyside]] || [[South Yorkshire]] ||[[Tyne and Wear]] || [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]] || [[West Yorkshire]]\n|-\n| [[Metropolitan borough|Metropolitan district]]|| 1974 || 36 || \n{{div col|small=no}}\n*[[Metropolitan Borough of Bolton|Bolton]]\n*[[Metropolitan Borough of Bury|Bury]]\n*[[Manchester]]\n*[[Metropolitan Borough of Oldham|Oldham]]\n*[[Metropolitan Borough of Rochdale|Rochdale]]\n*[[City of Salford|Salford]]\n*[[Metropolitan Borough of Stockport|Stockport]]\n*[[Tameside]]\n*[[Trafford]]\n*[[Metropolitan Borough of Wigan|Wigan]]\n{{div col end}}\n| \n{{div col|small=no}}\n*[[Metropolitan Borough of Knowsley|Knowsley]]\n*[[Liverpool]]\n*[[Metropolitan Borough of Sefton|Sefton]]\n*[[Metropolitan Borough of St Helens|St Helens]]\n*[[Metropolitan Borough of Wirral|Wirral]]\n{{div col end}}\n|\n{{div col|small=no}}\n*[[Metropolitan Borough of Barnsley|Barnsley]]\n*[[Metropolitan Borough of Doncaster|Doncaster]]\n*[[Metropolitan Borough of Rotherham|Rotherham]]\n*[[City of Sheffield|Sheffield]]\n{{div col end}}\n|\n{{div col|small=no}}\n*[[Metropolitan Borough of Gateshead|Gateshead]]\n*[[Newcastle upon Tyne]]\n*[[North Tyneside]]\n*[[South Tyneside]]\n*[[City of Sunderland|Sunderland]]\n{{div col end}}\n|\n{{div col|small=no}}\n*[[Birmingham]]\n*[[Coventry]]\n*[[Dudley (borough)|Dudley]